00:01:07,350 --> 00:01:08,600
Story of the Week.

11
00:01:08,600 --> 00:01:13,337
"Getting Fitter" as Grounds for Dismissal – Cloudflare's AI Paradox

12
00:01:13,337 --> 00:01:22,150
On May 8, 2026, Cloudflare reported a record quarter — and simultaneously laid off 20 percent of its workforce .

13
00:01:22,150 --> 00:01:25,525
1,100 employees are losing their jobs.

14
00:01:25,525 --> 00:01:33,587
And the company says it openly: not losses, not market downturns — AI productivity gains made these positions obsolete.

15
00:01:33,587 --> 00:01:39,862
CEO Matthew Prince put it internally like this: "Just because you're fit doesn't mean you can't get fitter" .

16
00:01:39,862 --> 00:01:44,112
No euphemism, no restructuring label — a direct admission.

17
00:01:44,112 --> 00:01:55,012
Since November 2025, Prince has been describing internally a "tipping point" at which teams suddenly became "two, ten, even a hundred times more productive" .

18
00:01:55,012 --> 00:02:02,137
Internal AI usage rose 600% in three months — and that didn't leave headcount decisions unaffected.

19
00:02:02,137 --> 00:02:12,112
The numbers speak for themselves: Q1 2026 brought $639.8M in revenue, up 34% year-over-year .

20
00:02:12,112 --> 00:02:14,937
It's the strongest quarter in the company's history.

21
00:02:14,937 --> 00:02:27,625
At the same time, the net loss rose from $53.2M to $62M — a sign that the layoffs are driven primarily by strategic repositioning rather than cost-cutting pressure .

22
00:02:27,625 --> 00:02:32,887
All areas except sales with directly measurable revenue accountability are affected.

23
00:02:32,887 --> 00:02:34,462
What comes after the layoff?

24
00:02:34,462 --> 00:02:45,625
Prince announced that Cloudflare will have more employees in 2027 than in 2026  — both a CEO promise and a PR signal, verifiable only in 18 months.

25
00:02:45,625 --> 00:02:51,300
That's the stated rhythm: first efficiency through AI, then growth into new areas.

26
00:02:51,300 --> 00:02:58,612
Not permanent headcount reduction — but a recalibration that first lays off, then rehires, for different roles.

27
00:02:58,612 --> 00:03:12,412
Why this matters for us: This is one of the most prominent and direct public acknowledgments that a profitable tech company is explicitly and unambiguously naming AI efficiency as the primary driver of a mass layoff .

28
00:03:12,412 --> 00:03:22,825
Earlier cases like IBM (2023) or Amazon (2024) cited AI as one of several factors — Cloudflare makes it the central narrative.

29
00:03:22,825 --> 00:03:26,450
Not recession, not industry crisis — technology.

30
00:03:26,450 --> 00:03:34,300
The narrative from many companies that AI creates more jobs than it destroys now has a concrete, high-profile counterexample.

31
00:03:34,300 --> 00:03:42,225
For IT professionals, knowledge workers, and everyone in support-adjacent roles, this is a signal that should be taken seriously.

32
00:03:42,225 --> 00:03:53,862
Coincidentally: The US IT sector lost 13,000 jobs in April 2026, and the IT unemployment rate rose from 3.6% to 3.8% .

33
00:03:53,862 --> 00:04:05,050
A single month is not a statistically valid basis for a trend conclusion — monthly fluctuations of ±5,000–8,000 IT positions are historically normal.

34
00:04:05,050 --> 00:04:11,850
As a data point, however, it shows that AI-driven restructuring is measurably arriving in the industry.

35
00:04:11,850 --> 00:04:16,475
Bottom Line: The question is no longer whether AI displaces jobs.

36
00:04:16,475 --> 00:04:27,375
The question is at what pace, in which areas — and whether companies communicate as transparently as Cloudflare, or hide the same decisions behind restructuring euphemisms.

37
00:04:27,375 --> 00:04:28,712
More Top Stories.

38
00:04:28,712 --> 00:04:33,250
Anthropic + Blackstone + Goldman: Claude for the Mid-Market.

39
00:04:33,250 --> 00:04:44,962
Anthropic is founding a new, yet-to-be-named company together with Blackstone, Hellman & Friedman, Goldman Sachs, General Atlantic, Apollo, GIC, and Sequoia Capital .

40
00:04:44,962 --> 00:04:53,762
The goal: bringing Claude to companies that have so far fallen through the cracks — community banks, manufacturing businesses, regional hospitals.

41
00:04:54,687 --> 00:05:02,325
The model is interesting: not pure software licensing, but embedded "Applied AI Engineers" on-site with the customer .

42
00:05:02,325 --> 00:05:10,887
Anthropic is positioning itself between large consultancies like Accenture and Deloitte on one side and self-service API access on the other.

43
00:05:10,887 --> 00:05:18,912
CFO Krishna Rao puts it precisely: "Enterprise demand for Claude is significantly outpacing any single delivery model" .

44
00:05:18,912 --> 00:05:26,012
The new company explicitly targets firms that don't have the internal resources to deploy frontier AI independently .

45
00:05:26,012 --> 00:05:37,962
For the BKS Lab context, this means: the market for AI implementation services is growing massively right now — and Anthropic itself is becoming a competitor in the consulting segment.

46
00:05:37,962 --> 00:05:44,900
Anthropic Mythos: AI Finds 423 Firefox Bugs – Including One 15 Years Old.

47
00:05:44,900 --> 00:05:52,525
Anthropic's security model Mythos helped Mozilla fix 423 bugs in April 2026 alone .

48
00:05:52,525 --> 00:06:00,325
In April 2025 it was 31 — an increase of 1,265% in twelve months.

49
00:06:00,325 --> 00:06:09,650
Among them: a 15-year-old vulnerability in the HTML parser and critical sandbox vulnerabilities with bug bounties of up to $20,000 .

50
00:06:09,650 --> 00:06:19,887
Mythos creates compromised code patches and uses them to automatically test its own security boundaries — a self-referential approach with no human equivalent to date .

51
00:06:19,887 --> 00:06:26,775
Mozilla engineers still write all the actual patches; automation of patching itself is not yet possible.

52
00:06:26,775 --> 00:06:33,687
Brian Grinstead, Distinguished Engineer at Mozilla, sums it up: "These things are actually just suddenly very good" .

53
00:06:33,687 --> 00:06:38,162
The caveat: the same tool that finds bugs could also benefit attackers .

54
00:06:38,162 --> 00:06:42,350
Mythos is a dual-use tool — Mozilla uses it defensively.

55
00:06:42,350 --> 00:06:46,712
Anyone deploying it offensively finds the same vulnerabilities.

56
00:06:46,712 --> 00:06:59,250
The 12 documented flaws are now public — a deliberate step toward transparency, but one that simultaneously shows what potential AI security models would have for attackers before patches are available.

57
00:06:59,250 --> 00:07:05,187
GPT-5.5 Instant: OpenAI Sets New ChatGPT Standard.

58
00:07:05,187 --> 00:07:12,775
OpenAI has rolled out GPT-5.5 Instant as the new default model for all ChatGPT users .

59
00:07:12,775 --> 00:07:19,750
